Allow standard passes to be disabled by command line options.

This supports simple binary flags that either suppress the pass or do nothing. i.e. -disable-mypass=false has no effect. These should be converted to boolOrDefault in order to use applyOverride.

### overridePass() {#a44e47b2bfc045db917bcbfbaf8be40ac}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>static IdentifyingPassPtr overridePass (<a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#af8dcbb0c9f8f0e566a07488f68418d5b">AnalysisID</a> StandardID, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/identifyingpassptr">IdentifyingPassPtr</a> TargetID)</>}
  labels = {["static"]}>
Allow standard passes to be disabled by the command line, regardless of who is adding the pass.

StandardID is the pass identified in the standard pass pipeline and provided to addPass(). It may be a target-specific <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/callingconv/#abdf8cf606905c10634e831390981b0ed">ID</a> in the case that the target directly adds its own pass, but in that case we harmlessly fall through.

TargetID is the pass that the target has configured to override StandardID.

StandardID may be a pseudo <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/callingconv/#abdf8cf606905c10634e831390981b0ed">ID</a>. In that case TargetID is the name of the real pass to run. This allows multiple options to control a single pass depending on where in the pipeline that pass is added.

Definition at line <a href="#l00292">292</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/codegen/targetpassconfig-cpp">TargetPassConfig.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

<Link id="l00397" /><CodeLine lineNumber="397"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// empty, but it is a convenient way to suppress or replace specific passes</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00398" /><CodeLine lineNumber="398"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// that are part of a standard pass pipeline without overridding the entire</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00399" /><CodeLine lineNumber="399"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// pipeline. This mechanism allows target options to inherit a standard pass&#39;s</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00400" /><CodeLine lineNumber="400"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// user interface. For example, a target may disable a standard pass by</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00401" /><CodeLine lineNumber="401"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// default by substituting a pass ID of zero, and the user may still enable</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01089" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1089"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Add the complete set of target-independent postISel code generator passes.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01090" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1090"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01091" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1091"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This can be read as the standard order of major LLVM CodeGen stages. Stages</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01092" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1092"><Highlight kind="comment">/// with nontrivial configuration or multiple passes are broken out below in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01093" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1093"><Highlight kind="comment">/// add%Stage routines.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01094" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1094"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01095" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1095"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Any TargetPassConfig::addXX routine may be overriden by the Target. The</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01096" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1096"><Highlight kind="comment">/// addPre/Post methods with empty header implementations allow injecting</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01097" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1097"><Highlight kind="comment">/// target-specific fixups just before or after major stages. Additionally,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01098" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1098"><Highlight kind="comment">/// targets have the flexibility to change pass order within a stage by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01099" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1099"><Highlight kind="comment">/// overriding default implementation of add%Stage routines below. Each</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01100" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1100"><Highlight kind="comment">/// technique has maintainability tradeoffs because alternate pass orders are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01101" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1101"><Highlight kind="comment">/// not well supported. addPre/Post works better if the target pass is easily</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01102" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1102"><Highlight kind="comment">/// tied to a common pass. But if it has subtle dependencies on multiple passes,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01103" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1103"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the target should override the stage instead.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01104" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1104"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01105" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1105"><Highlight kind="comment">/// TODO: We could use a single addPre/Post(ID) hook to allow pass injection</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01106" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1106"><Highlight kind="comment">/// before/after any target-independent pass. But it&#39;s currently overkill.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01107" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1107" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetpassconfig/#a821092b65a0bd12e6aab341164fd4e93"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">void</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetpassconfig/#a821092b65a0bd12e6aab341164fd4e93">TargetPassConfig::addMachinePasses</a>() &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
